        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "5e05f11c40bc0fd0",
        "text": "03/15/17\n\nIn any computer history museum, there’s a lot of talks about how to access a media from a decade ago. Is it enough to emulate a machine that doesn’t exist anymore ? Emulators and simulators, we have plenty of. Is there any way to cause any media to be persistent, else than doing a lot and a lot of copies, and keeping track of all those copies ?\n\nInstead of thinking of it like a (beautiful) mess, the FedWiki framework sustains the idea that multiple copies should be part of the core process. Hence, there is no canonical version of the document in a special place. There is no special and sacred place for the document to be.\n\nThough that might be an idea that some scholars may abhor. Instead of a canonical version of the text, a fluid state, that might be altered and refreshed, keeping memories of its states.\n\nA software like word has formatted decades of digital writing, of what it is to write on a computer.\nHow can we stray away from it ? FedWiki is full of drag and dropping of content, backlinks, weaving relationships between sources and content. And sometimes, when someone ask for a feature to be implemented (which is the nature of an open-source project: new experimental features answer queries in real time, debug happens day after day), it is interesting to see what already exists and could be used in a different way.\n\nThink of it as accidental features. For example, one might complain about the need for a suggestion/editing mode. But there is a difference between an editor and an equal collaborator — perhaps one does not need to point out \"you should rewrite your text\" and actually move ahead and do it.\n\nSomeone wrote a pages full of questions, Ward forked that page and obliterated the questions by answering/overwriting them, paragraph by paragraph. But unexpectedly, each paragraph remembers what it once was, thus proposing a side by side view of questions and answers.\n\nOne might think this as the answer to something called \"Word\". A word doesn’t hold much.\nA paragraph holds an idea, it’s a more sound syntaxical unit. In Fedwiki, pressing the return button creates an independent paragraph, traceable, drag-eable. Making it easy to re-organize the text.\n\nBeyond single words let’s play with verses and parallel universes.\n\nThe syntax of course evolves with digital writing — the burst emission of Twitter might also affect longer text, but we might as well look at how some academic cram more than 4 ideas in a paragraph because of the limited space of the journal hosting the paper.\n\nMore than ever, the point is legibility, clarity — and perhaps the authenticity of a trace (through authentification process, digital signatures and so on).\n\nInstead of archiving a text as a single unit, we might want to integrate the thought-process.\nLet’s archive steps — the possibility to replay a process, a growth, a bifurcation.\n\nLet’s bring out the forks to the FEAST."
      },
